# Commit Conventions

This repo uses standard [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org) - **no gitmoji, no custom emoji prefixes**. This is non-negotiable.

## Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>
```

## Allowed types

| Type | Use when |
|---|---|
| `feat` | New user-visible feature |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `chore` | Maintenance that doesn't fit elsewhere (deps, tooling, config) |
| `refactor` | Internal restructure, no behavior change |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `style` | Formatting/whitespace only |
| `build` | Build system, packaging |
| `ci` | CI/CD pipeline only |
| `test` | Tests only |
| `revert` | Reverts a previous commit |

Breaking changes: append `!` after the type/scope (e.g. `feat(api)!: ...`) or add a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer.

## Rules

- Only use the types above - do not invent new ones (e.g. no `hotfix`, `WIP`, `boom`, `dep-add`, `dep-rm`).
- Subject in the imperative mood, no trailing period.
- Scope is optional but encouraged - reuse an existing scope from `git log --oneline -50` when one fits.
- Never add gitmoji/emoji prefixes when authoring a commit by hand, even though this repo's Commitizen config (`cz_gitmoji` in `.cz-config.js`) auto-generates a gitmoji-prefixed `bump(release): ...` commit during `cz bump` / the CI `bump.yml` workflow - that one is machine-generated, not hand-authored, and is the only exception.
